former boxing and MMA fighter)

74
00:04:32,770 --> 00:04:35,040
They're the representative players
of Bloody Game.

75
00:04:35,310 --> 00:04:37,450
They'll participate in the game
as Team P2.

76
00:04:38,610 --> 00:04:40,010
This is Team P3.

77
00:04:40,720 --> 00:04:41,750
Hong Jin Ho.

78
00:04:41,750 --> 00:04:42,820
(Hong Jin Ho, pro poker player,
the winner of "The Genius 1")

79
00:04:42,820 --> 00:04:43,820
Xitsuh.

80
00:04:43,820 --> 00:04:45,390
(Xitsuh, rapper,
early admission to BYU in the US)

81
00:04:45,550 --> 00:04:46,590
Choi Hye Seon.

82
00:04:46,590 --> 00:04:47,760
(Choi Hye Seon, data specialist
at a consulting firm in London)

83
00:04:47,920 --> 00:04:48,960
Heo Seong Beom.

84
00:04:48,960 --> 00:04:50,190
(Heo Seong Beom, AI researcher at KAIST,
Graduated from Korea Science Academy)

85
00:04:50,760 --> 00:04:53,160
They're the players who showed
great performance on Bloody Game Three.

86
00:04:53,430 --> 00:04:55,700
They'll participate in the game
as Team P3.

87
00:04:56,730 --> 00:04:58,100
This is Team Challenger.

88
00:04:58,770 --> 00:04:59,830
Kim Kyoung Hoon.

89
00:04:59,830 --> 00:05:00,970
(Kim Kyoung Hoon, businessman,
second-place winner of "The Genius 4")

90
00:05:01,070 --> 00:05:02,100
Kim You Hyun.

91
00:05:02,100 --> 00:05:03,570
(Kim You Hyun, pro poker player,
was on "The Genius 3" and "The Genius 4")

92
00:05:03,770 --> 00:05:04,810
Kim Nam Hee.

93
00:05:04,810 --> 00:05:06,440
(Kim Nam Hee,
an anchor-turned-TV personality)

94
00:05:06,640 --> 00:05:07,710
Kang Ji Hoo.

95
00:05:07,710 --> 00:05:09,410
(Kang Ji Hoo,
a mathematical sciences major at KAIST)

96
00:05:09,580 --> 00:05:12,110
The four players' survival skills
were verified...

97
00:05:12,110 --> 00:05:14,550
through various survival shows.

98
00:05:15,580 --> 00:05:17,520
They're trying again on a survival show.

99
00:05:17,720 --> 00:05:19,850
They'll participate in the game
as Team Challenger.

100
00:05:20,760 --> 00:05:21,990
This is Team Rookie.

101
00:05:22,890 --> 00:05:23,890
Kwak Beom.

102
00:05:23,890 --> 00:05:24,960
(Kwak Beom, comedian,
KBS' 27th batch comedian)

103
00:05:25,130 --> 00:05:26,160
Lee Gwan Hee.

104
00:05:26,160 --> 00:05:27,300
(Lee Gwan Hee, pro basketball player,
BA in Physical Education, Yonsei Univ.)

105
00:05:27,430 --> 00:05:28,500
Shin Seung Yong.

106
00:05:28,500 --> 00:05:29,560
(Shin Seung Yong, doctor,
Seoul National University graduate)

107
00:05:29,660 --> 00:05:30,800
Choi Yeon Cheong.

108
00:05:30,800 --> 00:05:31,800
(Choi Yeon Cheong, actress,
Mensa member with an IQ of 156)

109
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:33,500
These four players...

110
00:05:33,500 --> 00:05:36,640
have never participated
in a brain survival show,

111
00:05:36,640 --> 00:05:39,640
but they're players with the power
to turn the tide of the game.

112
00:05:40,210 --> 00:05:42,510
They're joining a brain survival show
for the first time.

113
00:05:42,710 --> 00:05:44,680
They'll participate in the game
as Team Rookie.

114
00:05:45,580 --> 00:05:47,150
Players from the five teams,

115
00:05:47,150 --> 00:05:49,080
survive by
engaging in intense team play...

116
00:05:49,280 --> 00:05:52,090
based on your survival tactics.

117
00:05:53,650 --> 00:05:55,460
"Gosh, this is indeed fresh."

118
00:05:55,620 --> 00:05:57,390
That's what I thought. Also,

119
00:05:57,390 --> 00:05:59,690
we were divided into teams
like Team P1, Team P2, and Team P3.

120
00:05:59,760 --> 00:06:03,400
I think my team, Team P3,
seems like a strong one.

121
00:06:03,500 --> 00:06:06,830
There's no other team that could beat us.

122
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,540
"Can you do it? Can you take us on?"

123
00:06:09,540 --> 00:06:11,010
Honestly speaking,

124
00:06:11,740 --> 00:06:14,040
there's no player
I'm most closely watching.

125
00:06:14,310 --> 00:06:16,140
I think Team P3 will do well...

126
00:06:16,140 --> 00:06:18,180
because Jin Ho and Xitsuh...

127
00:06:18,180 --> 00:06:19,380
are joining Bloody Game...

128
00:06:19,380 --> 00:06:21,750
for the third time, not any other shows.

129
00:06:21,750 --> 00:06:23,450
And they were in the most recent season.

130
00:06:23,550 --> 00:06:26,490
They have overwhelmingly
more experience in it.

131
00:06:26,590 --> 00:06:27,860
The person
who left a strong impression on me?

132
00:06:28,420 --> 00:06:30,090
The first season's winner, Lee Tae Gyun.

133
00:06:30,160 --> 00:06:31,590
I thought,
"Looks like we have a strong opponent."

134
00:06:31,660 --> 00:06:34,360
"They'll be a scary opponent."

135
00:06:34,830 --> 00:06:36,460
Objectively speaking,

136
00:06:36,700 --> 00:06:39,500
Team P3 seemed outstandingly strong
when it came to game capabilities.

137
00:06:39,630 --> 00:06:42,740
But you can't survive here
just with your brains.

138
00:06:42,970 --> 00:06:44,070
Our team is stronger.

139
00:06:44,070 --> 00:06:46,070
We're the originals.

140
00:06:46,440 --> 00:06:49,240
The original restaurant
is supposed to be better.

141
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:52,580
We're the first players
of Bloody Game One.

142
00:06:52,680 --> 00:06:55,850
No matter how well they do,
they can't beat us.

143
00:06:55,850 --> 00:06:58,850
I did feel Hong Jin Ho and Xitsuh
were a little threatening,

144
00:06:59,790 --> 00:07:03,360
but even with those two,
they can't beat Lee Tae Gyun.

145
00:07:03,360 --> 00:07:06,090
They may have higher stats,

146
00:07:06,090 --> 00:07:07,660
but we have this teamwork...

147
00:07:07,660 --> 00:07:09,730
that we built strongly
in the first season.

148
00:07:09,730 --> 00:07:12,800
Team P3 is slightly targeted,
but they can't beat Team P1.

149
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:15,070
The first ones are the best,
no matter what.

150
00:07:15,070 --> 00:07:16,800
The originals are the best,

151
00:07:16,800 --> 00:07:19,840
and there have been no other shows
that beat their first seasons.

152
00:07:19,840 --> 00:07:23,140
(Team P3 with experience
versus Team P1 with seasoned players)

153
00:07:23,680 --> 00:07:26,450
Soon, the first game will begin.

154
00:07:27,210 --> 00:07:29,280
Depending on the result of the first game,

155
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:30,680
only four teams...

156
00:07:30,680 --> 00:07:33,350
will enter the Bloody Mansion...

157
00:07:33,650 --> 00:07:35,290
and participate in the Money Challenge.

158
00:07:36,460 --> 00:07:41,460
Your legs are currently bound
with a passcode-locked padlock.

159
00:07:42,200 --> 00:07:44,470
Solve the question
that will be given soon,

160
00:07:44,470 --> 00:07:45,670
figure out the passcode,

161
00:07:45,670 --> 00:07:47,200
and escape from here.

162
00:07:47,570 --> 00:07:50,670
Everyone on the team
has to fully get out of the chair...

163
00:07:50,670 --> 00:07:52,340
to be considered a successful escape.

164
00:07:52,940 --> 00:07:55,380
The team to escape last,
ending up at the bottom,

165
00:07:55,640 --> 00:07:57,510
will all be eligible for elimination.

166
00:07:57,650 --> 00:07:59,950
They may not enter the Bloody Mansion,

167
00:08:00,850 --> 00:08:04,190
and they must remain in the outdoors
and survive.

168
00:08:04,390 --> 00:08:06,490
Darn it. This is crazy.

169
00:08:08,520 --> 00:08:10,460
I thought,
"I'm ruined. Something's gone wrong."

170
00:08:10,620 --> 00:08:12,890
I thought I'd die of hypothermia
if I were to sleep outdoors...

171
00:08:12,890 --> 00:08:14,730
in these wet clothes.

172
00:08:14,730 --> 00:08:17,870
I can't imagine how hard it's going to be.

173
00:08:18,230 --> 00:08:22,240
Soon, the question you can answer
to get the passcode...

174
00:08:22,440 --> 00:08:23,970
will be revealed on the monitor.

175
00:08:24,370 --> 00:08:26,140
There are three questions in total.

176
00:08:26,570 --> 00:08:30,740
Each question will be revealed
on repeat every 30 seconds.

177
00:08:31,250 --> 00:08:33,380
The passcode
that can unlock the padlock...

178
00:08:33,650 --> 00:08:36,550
is the sum of the values obtained
by multiplying all three questions.

179
00:08:38,250 --> 00:08:41,890
Now, we'll start
the first-come, first-served team game.

180
00:08:43,460 --> 00:08:47,430
(1st question)

181
00:08:56,940 --> 00:09:00,470
Wait, that's 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6...
Isn't it about strokes?

182
00:09:00,510 --> 00:09:02,380
- Then why is the 1st one 4?
- That doesn't work...

183
00:09:03,180 --> 00:09:05,580
Some kind of English was written
for the first question.

184
00:09:05,850 --> 00:09:06,910
"What is this?"

185
00:09:06,910 --> 00:09:09,950
I thought it was
a Caesar cipher-type problem.

186
00:09:09,950 --> 00:09:11,290
But it didn't work out.

187
00:09:11,920 --> 00:09:15,420
TAC? TNA? Those were the words
I saw for the first time.

188
00:09:15,420 --> 00:09:18,130
It was so hard. As soon as I saw it,
I went, "What does it mean?"

189
00:09:18,890 --> 00:09:20,900
Gosh. Do you have any idea?

190
00:09:21,230 --> 00:09:22,830
- Do you?
- No, not yet.

191
00:09:24,470 --> 00:09:27,600
I thought it was some kind of rule
that maps letters and numbers...

192
00:09:27,600 --> 00:09:29,140
one-to-one in a symmetric way,

193
00:09:29,140 --> 00:09:31,470
making them divisible
by the ones or tens digit.

194
00:09:31,540 --> 00:09:33,310
That's how I tried to approach it.

195
00:09:34,210 --> 00:09:36,340
I tried to approach the question
with the order of the alphabet.

196
00:09:36,340 --> 00:09:38,080
I also tried approaching it
using operators.

197
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:40,250
I also tried thinking
in terms of the number of shapes.

198
00:09:40,380 --> 00:09:44,150
Nothing made sense,
so I had to think for a while.

199
00:09:44,220 --> 00:09:45,350
Does "T" mean addition?

200
00:09:45,350 --> 00:09:46,620
If we add A and C in order,

201
00:09:46,620 --> 00:09:48,060
it'd be 1 and 3,
so it's natural that it's 4.

202
00:09:48,060 --> 00:09:49,490
But the N and A don't make sense...

203
00:09:49,490 --> 00:09:52,560
because N is 14th and A is 1st.

204
00:09:52,760 --> 00:09:55,660
- Wait. Fourteen and...
- I don't think that's the case.

205
00:09:55,930 --> 00:09:58,500
Then it'd be impossible
to have the I and P.

206
00:09:58,500 --> 00:09:59,570
- Oh, you're right.
- It's impossible to guess their values.

207
00:09:59,570 --> 00:10:01,300
- You're right.
- It's never something mathematical.

208
00:10:01,800 --> 00:10:02,870
This must be a brain teaser.

209
00:10:02,870 --> 00:10:05,740
Honestly, it was
about something mathematical...

210
00:10:05,740 --> 00:10:07,510
that I had no idea about.

211
00:10:07,580 --> 00:10:08,580
So I told Hye Seon,

212
00:10:08,580 --> 00:10:12,480
"Hye Seon, this must be something
that an empty head should solve."

213
00:10:12,780 --> 00:10:15,520
"Hye Seon,
this isn't a difficult question."

214
00:10:15,980 --> 00:10:17,320
It must be way simpler.

215
00:10:18,520 --> 00:10:20,850
It's way simpler. It must be ridiculous.

216
00:10:20,890 --> 00:10:22,660
How can the two fours have the same value?

217
00:10:23,120 --> 00:10:25,030
How can TAC and GOD be the same thing?

218
00:10:29,060 --> 00:10:30,970
This is insane.

219
00:10:30,970 --> 00:10:32,630
If you reverse them,
they're the names of animals.

220
00:10:32,630 --> 00:10:34,030
"Cat, ant, dog."

221
00:10:34,540 --> 00:10:36,140
Wait. Then why is "cat" four?

222
00:10:36,400 --> 00:10:37,810
Why is "cat" 4 and "ant" is 6?

223
00:10:37,810 --> 00:10:38,910
The number of legs!

224
00:10:38,910 --> 00:10:40,410
Wait. PIG, four.

225
00:10:40,410 --> 00:10:42,510
- Then that's 4, and MAN is 2.
- MAN is 2.

226
00:10:42,510 --> 00:10:43,940
- Then that's 24.
- The 2 of them...

227
00:10:43,940 --> 00:10:46,150
- It's 24.
- Hye Seon solved the 1st one.

228
00:10:46,310 --> 00:10:47,750
- Nice.
- You see?

229
00:10:47,750 --> 00:10:48,880
It should've been reversed.

230
00:10:49,220 --> 00:10:53,290
As soon as Xitsuh gave me a hint
that this is close to a brain teaser,

231
00:10:53,390 --> 00:10:55,960
I tried reading the words reversed,
and I could see the names of animals.

232
00:10:56,090 --> 00:10:57,090
TAC?

233
00:10:57,090 --> 00:10:59,530
In reverse, it's "cat."

234
00:10:59,960 --> 00:11:01,800
TNA? That's "ant."

235
00:11:01,800 --> 00:11:03,660
Then what's with the numbers 4 and 6?
That's the number of their legs.

236
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:07,330
NAM. And GIP.

237
00:11:07,330 --> 00:11:09,300
In reverse, it's "pig" and "man."

238
00:11:09,470 --> 00:11:12,010
A human has 2 legs, and a pig has 4 legs,

239
00:11:12,010 --> 00:11:14,040
So the answer is 24.

240
00:11:14,940 --> 00:11:16,280
Does anyone know the answer to number one?

241
00:11:16,740 --> 00:11:17,950
No, I have no idea.

242
00:11:18,950 --> 00:11:21,780
"Cat, ant, dog."

243
00:11:23,280 --> 00:11:25,290
And it's "pig" and "man."

244
00:11:25,290 --> 00:11:27,090
It's...

245
00:11:27,190 --> 00:11:28,860
"Cat" is four. In other words,

246
00:11:29,060 --> 00:11:31,360
"ant" is 6, and "dog" is 4.

247
00:11:31,860 --> 00:11:33,290
"Man, pig."

248
00:11:33,890 --> 00:11:36,230
Four... It's "pig."

249
00:11:36,230 --> 00:11:38,000
That's 24.

250
00:11:40,430 --> 00:11:43,600
(Team Rookie hasn't
quite gotten the hang of it yet.)

251
00:11:43,600 --> 00:11:46,510
The members of other teams
have experience,

252
00:11:46,610 --> 00:11:49,240
and we're a team
with non-experienced members.

253
00:11:49,580 --> 00:11:51,580
The other teams
would share their opinions,

254
00:11:51,580 --> 00:11:53,680
giving hints to each other.

255
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:55,080
We failed to communicate.

256
00:11:55,250 --> 00:11:57,350
I could feel that our team members
were flustered too.

257
00:11:57,420 --> 00:12:00,350
As we're chained together,

258
00:12:00,650 --> 00:12:02,990
we could tell we were flustered.

259
00:12:04,390 --> 00:12:07,630
(2nd question)

260
00:12:09,360 --> 00:12:10,630
Gosh, what is that?

261
00:12:10,900 --> 00:12:13,670
I couldn't get the hang
of the second question at all.

262
00:12:17,970 --> 00:12:19,270
Question number two? It's about numbers.

263
00:12:19,640 --> 00:12:21,880
Since I like numbers,
I've been looking at it for a while.

264
00:12:21,910 --> 00:12:22,910
But I couldn't solve it.

265
00:12:22,910 --> 00:12:24,280
It's become more difficult.

266
00:12:24,550 --> 00:12:26,050
Since we have experienced ones,

267
00:12:26,050 --> 00:12:28,650
the level of difficulty
has gone up higher.

268
00:12:29,050 --> 00:12:30,220
"What is this?"

269
00:12:30,320 --> 00:12:32,190
If it's 1, 8, 1, 8, 1,
then it's 1, 8, 1, 8, 1.

270
00:12:32,190 --> 00:12:33,250
One's 1, 2, 3, 4, 5,

271
00:12:33,250 --> 00:12:34,490
and the other one is 3, question mark,
3, 3, 3...

272
00:12:34,790 --> 00:12:36,620
When I was wondering what that was,
the question changed again.

273
00:12:36,720 --> 00:12:39,930
(3rd question)

274
00:12:40,230 --> 00:12:41,560
What? It ended already?

275
00:12:42,200 --> 00:12:43,300
"What is this?"

276
00:12:43,660 --> 00:12:45,470
It's confusing
even if we keep looking at one question,

277
00:12:45,470 --> 00:12:46,870
but they changed the question
every 30 seconds.

278
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:48,400
Gosh, this isn't going to be easy.

279
00:12:48,870 --> 00:12:50,370
The third question
had some Chinese characters.

280
00:12:50,370 --> 00:12:51,810
I didn't even get the meaning,
but they just came out.

281
00:12:52,510 --> 00:12:53,870
Does anyone get the hang of any question?

282
00:12:55,410 --> 00:12:56,610
It's all iffy, right?

283
00:12:57,040 --> 00:12:59,110
- I can't tell the Chinese letters.
- It's "king" and "bear."

284
00:13:00,150 --> 00:13:02,650
But it has to be a question you can solve
without knowing those letters.

285
00:13:03,820 --> 00:13:05,120
Is it about strokes?

286
00:13:06,320 --> 00:13:07,490
- Or Korean alphabets?
- Considering it's about strokes,

287
00:13:07,490 --> 00:13:08,890
that's too many, having 11.

288
00:13:10,820 --> 00:13:12,030
Eleven?

289
00:13:12,030 --> 00:13:13,390
How is "tree" 11?

290
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:16,760
There are people who can't read
Chinese characters,

291
00:13:16,760 --> 00:13:18,170
so I don't think
they gave out that question...

292
00:13:18,170 --> 00:13:19,570
to figure out Chinese characters.

293
00:13:20,370 --> 00:13:22,870
It's mok, jeon, gan, wang, gong.

294
00:13:23,200 --> 00:13:24,570
I don't think that's the answer.

295
00:13:24,970 --> 00:13:26,170
As for Chinese characters,

296
00:13:26,170 --> 00:13:27,640
I think the variables...

297
00:13:27,640 --> 00:13:29,310
are the horizontal strokes,
the vertical strokes,

298
00:13:29,310 --> 00:13:31,150
diagonal strokes,
and intersection strokes.

299
00:13:31,150 --> 00:13:32,510
There are four variables.

300
00:13:32,510 --> 00:13:35,050
It's either we assemble them
with addition or multiplication.

301
00:13:35,180 --> 00:13:36,480
Or we can choose 3 out of 4...

302
00:13:36,480 --> 00:13:38,590
and form a quadratic equation
and find its roots.

303
00:13:38,590 --> 00:13:40,750
We tried all possible operations,

304
00:13:41,120 --> 00:13:42,190
but we couldn't get it.

305
00:13:42,490 --> 00:13:44,320
The second question was really hard.

306
00:13:44,320 --> 00:13:46,160
I had no idea
about the third question too.

307
00:13:46,160 --> 00:13:49,130
We had to multiply the sum
of the three questions...

308
00:13:49,130 --> 00:13:50,400
to unlock the padlock.

309
00:13:50,530 --> 00:13:52,470
The only thing I could figure out
was that it was four digits.

310
00:13:52,730 --> 00:13:54,400
(Thinking)

311
00:13:54,900 --> 00:13:57,070
I thought I found out something amazing,

312
00:13:57,700 --> 00:13:59,040
but I couldn't figure out
anything after that.

313
00:13:59,040 --> 00:14:01,070
(Find the product of the answers
to the three problems.)

314
00:14:01,070 --> 00:14:03,010
(1st question, 2nd question, 3rd question)

315
00:14:03,580 --> 00:14:05,550
Hey, do you have any idea
what questions 2 and 3 might be about?

316
00:14:06,150 --> 00:14:07,150
Not at all.

317
00:14:07,650 --> 00:14:09,580
- It's frustrating.
- I have no idea.

318
00:14:11,120 --> 00:14:12,150
Darn it.

319
00:14:23,460 --> 00:14:24,900
Would it be better to use strength?

320
00:14:26,930 --> 00:14:29,940
I thought if I budged here and there,

321
00:14:30,040 --> 00:14:31,940
it'd get loose.

322
00:14:31,940 --> 00:14:34,640
But there was no space at all.

323
00:14:35,310 --> 00:14:37,440
The ropes were tied too tightly.

324
00:14:37,440 --> 00:14:39,980
It was raining, and the rope was wet,

325
00:14:39,980 --> 00:14:42,520
so it was even harder to untie it.

326
00:14:42,580 --> 00:14:45,390
In the second season,
we could break the chair.

327
00:14:45,390 --> 00:14:48,960
We could solve it physically.

328
00:14:53,090 --> 00:14:54,260
The thing is,

329
00:14:55,100 --> 00:14:56,660
there were bad precedents.

330
00:14:56,800 --> 00:14:59,830
They should think of solving the problems
and making it out.

331
00:14:59,830 --> 00:15:02,170
They'd just untie the rope
and break chairs.

332
00:15:02,340 --> 00:15:05,110
As the seasons go on,
the ropes have gotten tighter.

333
00:15:05,240 --> 00:15:06,810
Even the chairs are made of iron.

334
00:15:06,810 --> 00:15:08,480
We can't break it
because it isn't made of wood.

335
00:15:23,260 --> 00:15:24,560
- Is it getting loose?
- Yes.

336
00:15:24,660 --> 00:15:26,160
I'll loosen it quickly and help you.

337
00:15:26,930 --> 00:15:29,730
I almost didn't read the screen
when they showed me the screen.

338
00:15:30,000 --> 00:15:31,800
I thought I couldn't solve it
using my brain.

339
00:15:31,900 --> 00:15:34,530
As soon as I saw
Tae Gyun, Ji Min, and Sang Min,

340
00:15:34,530 --> 00:15:36,700
I thought I had to untie myself first,
no matter what.

341
00:15:37,040 --> 00:15:39,410
I saw how the ropes were tied on us...

342
00:15:39,540 --> 00:15:41,710
and how they should be untied.

343
00:15:42,210 --> 00:15:43,940
I thought I should untie them,

344
00:15:43,940 --> 00:15:45,910
whether I use my strength or other ways.

345
00:15:47,680 --> 00:15:49,550
I don't know where this starts.
To solve the questions first...

346
00:15:49,550 --> 00:15:51,220
Those who need to solve the questions
should go ahead and do so.

347
00:15:51,220 --> 00:15:52,290
Yes.

348
00:15:53,150 --> 00:15:55,290
Those who can solve them...
We should take two tracks.

349
00:15:55,720 --> 00:15:58,030
Everyone is good at something.

350
00:15:58,160 --> 00:16:00,030
The brains should use their heads.

351
00:16:00,130 --> 00:16:02,260
Athletes have to use their bodies.

352
00:16:09,900 --> 00:16:10,970
Hold on.

353
00:16:15,480 --> 00:16:16,580
I saw his legs,

354
00:16:16,580 --> 00:16:18,880
I noticed how tightly a cable tie...

355
00:16:18,880 --> 00:16:21,880
at the end of the knot was tied.

356
00:16:22,380 --> 00:16:25,150
I pulled it off, using all my strength.

357
00:16:48,010 --> 00:16:49,210
Darn, that guy is...

358
00:16:49,610 --> 00:16:51,450
He's a nutcase.

359
00:16:52,050 --> 00:16:54,180
At that moment,
unlocking the padlock wasn't the issue.

360
00:16:54,180 --> 00:16:55,780
I thought my bone would break.

361
00:16:55,780 --> 00:16:57,680
"What if they break my bone?"

362
00:16:57,680 --> 00:16:59,250
I had that thought, honestly.

363
00:16:59,390 --> 00:17:01,290
Gosh, we're already a mess on day one.

364
00:17:06,730 --> 00:17:07,760
We got it.

365
00:17:07,860 --> 00:17:09,100
Darn, we got it.

366
00:17:13,970 --> 00:17:15,870
Keun Woo, lay me down.

367
00:17:16,270 --> 00:17:17,370
Should I pull you down?

368
00:17:17,800 --> 00:17:18,810
Lay me down.

369
00:17:20,710 --> 00:17:22,140
- All the way down?
- Yes.

370
00:17:33,720 --> 00:17:34,720
Okay.

371
00:17:35,820 --> 00:17:36,860
There you go.

372
00:17:41,730 --> 00:17:42,960
Keep solving the problems.

373
00:17:43,260 --> 00:17:44,260
What do we do?

374
00:17:44,260 --> 00:17:46,130
Take your shoes off. I'll pull them off.

375
00:17:50,940 --> 00:17:51,940
Hey.

376
00:17:52,440 --> 00:17:53,570
Seung Jin.

377
00:17:53,870 --> 00:17:55,210
Please unlock mine too.

378
00:17:55,210 --> 00:17:56,280
Please unlock mine.

379
00:17:56,480 --> 00:17:57,480
Unlock yours?

380
00:17:57,480 --> 00:17:58,880
- Are you guys on the same team?
- Yes.

381
00:17:59,650 --> 00:18:00,950
How can a professional athlete
fail to unlock this?

382
00:18:00,950 --> 00:18:02,180
You're still an active athlete.

383
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:04,920
Darn.

384
00:18:05,150 --> 00:18:06,520
Why did you wear basketball shoes?

385
00:18:07,190 --> 00:18:08,360
Are you here to play basketball?

386
00:18:17,830 --> 00:18:20,530
That thought flashed through my mind.

387
00:18:21,100 --> 00:18:23,840
The moment where we shared potatoes
while shaking...

388
00:18:24,040 --> 00:18:26,540
at the outdoors camping site
while getting rained on.

389
00:18:27,370 --> 00:18:29,210
Could you put in some more strength, then?

390
00:18:30,210 --> 00:18:31,240
You want me to put in more strength?

391
00:18:31,240 --> 00:18:32,780
This is bad. Our team is in trouble.

392
00:18:32,780 --> 00:18:34,580
- Why?
- He wants me to put in more strength.

393
00:18:35,650 --> 00:18:37,320
Darn. I can't even loosen this.

394
00:18:38,020 --> 00:18:40,650
Our team would be the righteous sect
in martial arts fiction terms.

395
00:18:40,750 --> 00:18:42,990
When they throw a question at us,
we solve the question.

396
00:18:43,220 --> 00:18:44,860
I actually have no strength
to untie the rope.

397
00:18:45,030 --> 00:18:46,590
If we had a strong member,

398
00:18:46,590 --> 00:18:48,160
I'd go, "Untie the rope,"

399
00:18:48,260 --> 00:18:49,800
"and we'll go solve the problem."

400
00:18:50,100 --> 00:18:51,700
But we're all the same.

401
00:18:52,230 --> 00:18:53,870
Who's going to untie the ropes?

402
00:18:56,200 --> 00:18:57,670
Gosh, we'll stay outside just like this?

403
00:18:59,470 --> 00:19:01,210
Darn, Seong Beom. This isn't right.

404
00:19:01,780 --> 00:19:02,840
Let's solve it.

405
00:19:09,280 --> 00:19:14,120
A, B, C, D, E, F...

406
00:19:14,790 --> 00:19:15,790
Wait.

407
00:19:15,790 --> 00:19:17,960
A, B, C, D, E, F, G...

408
00:19:17,960 --> 00:19:19,960
H, I, J, K...

409
00:19:22,730 --> 00:19:23,830
A, B...

410
00:19:26,600 --> 00:19:28,340
I figured it out.

411
00:19:28,600 --> 00:19:30,470
Those are letters.

412
00:19:30,700 --> 00:19:33,510
They're K, B, F.

413
00:19:33,510 --> 00:19:34,670
And the one below that,

414
00:19:35,880 --> 00:19:37,780
- are E and C.
- You're right.

415
00:19:37,780 --> 00:19:39,510
So it's 53.

416
00:19:39,580 --> 00:19:42,780
When I saw the numbers,
they were 11, 2, 6.

417
00:19:42,850 --> 00:19:45,350
I thought,
"Wait, the number range isn't wide."

418
00:19:45,450 --> 00:19:48,120
Then it must be the English alphabet
or Hangul.

419
00:19:48,390 --> 00:19:50,290
So I tried Hangul, and it didn't work.

420
00:19:50,290 --> 00:19:51,790
I used the English alphabet instead,

421
00:19:51,790 --> 00:19:54,390
and I could see something similar
next to it.

422
00:19:54,690 --> 00:19:56,060
I thought it was a character for "wood,"

423
00:19:56,060 --> 00:19:58,770
but it turned out to be "K" in English.

424
00:19:59,100 --> 00:20:01,540
"If it's two, then it's a B.
Wait. That's a capital B."

425
00:20:02,470 --> 00:20:07,110
So it's like
the alphabet reflected in a mirror.

426
00:20:07,110 --> 00:20:09,510
I instantly recognized it
as a decalcomania.

427
00:20:09,640 --> 00:20:12,880
Seeing the letters below,
I could see E and C.

428
00:20:13,010 --> 00:20:14,510
That's how I figured out 53.

429
00:20:14,950 --> 00:20:17,450
Hey, multiply 24 and 53.

430
00:20:17,680 --> 00:20:19,690
- You mean 24 and 53?
- The 1st one is 24, right?

431
00:20:19,850 --> 00:20:20,990
I'm certain about it.

432
00:20:20,990 --> 00:20:22,060
Okay, then...

433
00:20:35,440 --> 00:20:36,900
For this battle...

434
00:20:36,900 --> 00:20:38,940
It's unlocked!

435
00:20:40,510 --> 00:20:41,940
Let's get out.

436
00:20:42,610 --> 00:20:45,210
When I multiplied them, I got 1,272.

437
00:20:45,310 --> 00:20:47,850
We knew the second problem
had a single-digit answer.

438
00:20:48,110 --> 00:20:50,520
It could've worked with any numbers.

439
00:20:50,620 --> 00:20:53,750
I thought, "What if the answer is two?"

440
00:20:53,750 --> 00:20:55,660
Then I thought, "Wait. Why two?"

441
00:20:56,160 --> 00:20:58,890
There's only one reason
for an answer to be between 2 and 3.

442
00:20:59,360 --> 00:21:00,390
A calendar.

443
00:21:00,390 --> 00:21:02,130
There are only 28 days in February.

444
00:21:02,560 --> 00:21:04,700
It was January 31, February 28,

445
00:21:05,430 --> 00:21:07,530
March 31, April 30...

446
00:21:07,530 --> 00:21:09,100
That's the pattern.

447
00:21:09,170 --> 00:21:11,070
I multiplied 1,272 and 2.

448
00:21:11,500 --> 00:21:12,910
Then I got 2,544.

449
00:21:13,070 --> 00:21:15,310
(Multiply the answers
from the three problems.)

450
00:21:15,310 --> 00:21:17,710
(Problem 1, Problem 2, Problem 3)

451
00:21:17,710 --> 00:21:20,580
- I cracked it!
- A hint will be revealed soon.

452
00:21:23,480 --> 00:21:25,320
- What is it?
- I don't know.

453
00:21:25,320 --> 00:21:26,690
- Help us get out of this.
- I won't tell you.

454
00:21:26,690 --> 00:21:27,750
Did you turn the numbers on the lock?

455
00:21:27,850 --> 00:21:29,090
- You were supposed to!
- Did you turn the numbers?

456
00:21:29,090 --> 00:21:30,160
Darn it.

457
00:21:30,160 --> 00:21:32,230
- Come on. Don't be an amateur.
- It's all right.

458
00:21:34,390 --> 00:21:35,460
Let's hurry.

459
00:21:35,460 --> 00:21:38,030
- Did you turn the numbers?
- The code is 2544.

460
00:21:38,500 --> 00:21:40,670
(Hovering over)

461
00:21:41,230 --> 00:21:42,240
- The code is 2544.
- Hey.

462
00:21:42,240 --> 00:21:43,870
- The code is 2544.
- Wait.

463
00:21:44,600 --> 00:21:45,910
- That's it.
- Give that to me.

464
00:21:45,910 --> 00:21:47,870
- We got it.
- Pull it out.

465
00:21:47,870 --> 00:21:49,080
- Turn the numbers.
- Okay.

466
00:21:49,140 --> 00:21:50,340
- Right here.
- The other way around.

467
00:21:50,610 --> 00:21:52,080
- Over here. It's 2544.
- Okay.

468
00:21:52,150 --> 00:21:53,150
(Clicking)

469
00:21:53,150 --> 00:21:54,180
- Hurry.
- We got it.

470
00:21:58,320 --> 00:22:01,390
- Xitsuh.
- Turn them.

471
00:22:01,390 --> 00:22:03,920
- Xitsuh. Tell us about the 3rd one.
- Just the 3rd one.

472
00:22:03,920 --> 00:22:06,560
- Just the third one.
- We'll tell you once we get out of this.

473
00:22:08,260 --> 00:22:09,260
There are so many.

474
00:22:09,360 --> 00:22:10,560
Help me.

475
00:22:11,330 --> 00:22:12,430
Could you tell us what it is?

476
00:22:12,430 --> 00:22:14,670
- Let me untie this first.
- Help me out. Then I'll tell you.

477
00:22:15,570 --> 00:22:16,770
Let's get out of here.

478
00:22:16,770 --> 00:22:18,040
- Could you help Hye Seon?
- Okay.

479
00:22:18,040 --> 00:22:19,070
- Wait.
- Hold on.

480
00:22:19,070 --> 00:22:20,210
- Could you help me out?
- Hey.

481
00:22:21,780 --> 00:22:23,340
One, two, three. All right.

482
00:22:23,580 --> 00:22:24,910
Come on.

483
00:22:27,180 --> 00:22:28,480
Arms up.

484
00:22:28,480 --> 00:22:30,020
- Wait.
- Arms up.

485
00:22:30,020 --> 00:22:31,050
- What is this?
- Arms up.

486
00:22:31,050 --> 00:22:32,320
Arms up. We got it.

487
00:22:38,260 --> 00:22:40,360
(Team P3 just began untying the ropes.)

488
00:22:42,730 --> 00:22:44,860
- Hey.
- No.

489
00:22:45,030 --> 00:22:46,070
- Okay.
- We got it.

490
00:22:47,170 --> 00:22:48,370
- Pull your arm out.
- Darn.

491
00:22:48,370 --> 00:22:49,440
- Let's go.
- Run.

492
00:22:49,840 --> 00:22:51,470
- Run.
- Come on!

493
00:22:51,470 --> 00:22:52,740
- Where is it?
- This is too much.

494
00:22:52,940 --> 00:22:53,940
- Do you have it?
- How...

495
00:22:54,170 --> 00:22:55,180
- Where are they?
- Let's go.

496
00:22:55,640 --> 00:22:56,740
- How many teams are left?
- Let's go.

497
00:22:59,650 --> 00:23:02,250
- Ji Min, help us before you go.
- Darn.

498
00:23:02,250 --> 00:23:03,580
Help us for old times' sake.

499
00:23:04,020 --> 00:23:05,920
- We'll return the favor.
- Help us. We'll return the favor.

500
00:23:06,120 --> 00:23:07,990
- You'd better.
- We will. Just the third one.

501
00:23:07,990 --> 00:23:09,390
- It's 2544.
- Okay.

502
00:23:09,390 --> 00:23:10,660
- Let's go.
- It's 2544.

503
00:23:12,030 --> 00:23:13,890
- Let's go.
- Let's go.

504
00:23:13,890 --> 00:23:14,990
(Team P1 escapes.)

505
00:23:15,330 --> 00:23:17,830
I really wanted to see you guys again.
Who knew we'd meet here?

506
00:23:25,840 --> 00:23:27,140
Did they crack it too?

507
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:28,640
Are we the last one?

508
00:23:28,880 --> 00:23:30,010
Darn it.

509
00:23:31,210 --> 00:23:32,310
These ropes are just insane.

510
00:23:38,550 --> 00:23:41,890
Gwan Hee was helping out another team.

511
00:23:41,890 --> 00:23:43,360
I saw that.

512
00:23:45,760 --> 00:23:48,130
Gwan Hee,
you have to help us get out of these.

513
00:23:48,130 --> 00:23:49,730
She said she'd give us the answer.

514
00:23:49,730 --> 00:23:50,760
Really?

515
00:23:50,930 --> 00:23:52,600
Once I use up my energy...

516
00:23:52,600 --> 00:23:53,970
Help us. And we'll give you the answer
before we leave.

517
00:23:54,800 --> 00:23:57,300
Did he think that
he was on "Single's Inferno?"

518
00:23:58,200 --> 00:23:59,570
After helping her untie the ropes,

519
00:24:00,670 --> 00:24:02,680
he also helped the guy next to her too.

520
00:24:04,780 --> 00:24:05,980
They're almost done.

521
00:24:06,580 --> 00:24:08,850
Jin Hyeong,
could you help us with this once?

522
00:24:11,020 --> 00:24:12,750
- Just this once.
- It's 2544.

523
00:24:12,750 --> 00:24:14,520
- It's 2544.
- What?

524
00:24:15,290 --> 00:24:16,290
It's 2544.

525
00:24:17,720 --> 00:24:18,730
It's not it.

526
00:24:20,890 --> 00:24:22,260
We had opened our lock anyway.

527
00:24:22,330 --> 00:24:25,060
I thought it would be more advantageous...

528
00:24:25,230 --> 00:24:27,300
